Ok, here's my pitch to explain the benefit. It mirrors the definition of the go HTTP server; there's a global instance you can summon when you need it, and ignore when you don't.

Here's the benefit.

Suppose I wanted write a function that checks if pulumi-experimental is enabled and does something.

```golang
func skip_checkpoints() {
   if getModuleLevelEnvVar() == "1"  {
       // ...do the thing
   }
}
```

This requires global state, which makes the test unable to be run in parallel, since it could conflict with other tests also modifying that global state in the same process. 

Instead, you could write:
```golang
func skipCheckpoints(env Environment) {
   if env.Get("PULUMI_EXPERIMENTAL") == "1"  {
       // ...do the thing
   }
}
```
and perform dependency injection of the Environment. Then you'd wrap your original code like this:

```golang
func skipCheckpointsWrapper() {
    var env = getGlobalEnv()
    skipCheckpoints(env)
}
```

The wrapper is what you'd use in your client code, but the version with D.I. is what you'd cover with a unit test. In general, we want unit tests to be pure and total so they can be isolated, so minimizing global state improves testability. That's the general goal of D.I. in this context.

--------

> It also forces each variable to be declared in the same scope, vs where they are used.

Yes. I believe all of our environment variables should be declared in a single location. I don't think we want env variable declarations scattered throughout the code. We should declare all configurables upfront in a single location where possible. This improves discoverability. It's true that means they are "further away" from where they're used, but their location is standardized, and only a single hop ("Jump to Definition") that colocates all of the environment variables. 

> In general, I think we should avoid tests depending on env vars. If functions need to be explicitly set to up to take the env bundle, they should take just the values they need as arguments

I agree that it's true we want to minimize unit tests that exercise features with environment variables. In practice we already have a number of locations that use them. To see those locations, enable this linter in golangci-lint: https://github.com/sivchari/tenv . Those are just the places that set env vars in tests that violate the lints.

As you move up the test pyramid, you'll inevitably have more coarse-grained tests that exercise larger sections of the codebase, some of which will test functionality with configurable toggles. The way to keep this most pure is to inject some `config` struct at each of those sites: i.e. each subsystem of Pulumi is initialized with the set of configurables it needs, following RAII and "fail fast" design methodologies. I agree that if you do that, you won't need to ever set env vars in your tests, because you can always inject your own value. But I worry we aren't far enough along to make that happen, as evidenced by the failing lints.

Does that make sense? I guess I'm trying to offer feedback on two fronts:
1. Why grouping together env vars in a single location is better than spreading them out.
2. Why having a single global Environment instance is better than having a collection of env vars instances (D.I. becomes more straightforward for higher-up-the-pyramid tests).

